Or do you just start writing?

00:40:14.330 --> 00:40:19.710
And do you allow it to
pivot from point-to-point?

00:40:19.710 --> 00:40:22.250 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Stacy Schiff: In short -- because
I could do this for several hours --

00:40:22.250 --> 00:40:24.840
it usually takes me
four to five years,

00:40:24.840 --> 00:40:27.730
of which I spend the first
three years in the archive.

00:40:27.730 --> 00:40:29.790
So I really have no idea
where the book begins.

00:40:29.790 --> 00:40:32.570
I have no idea what I'm
looking for necessarily.

00:40:32.570 --> 00:40:34.940
And I'm just kind of following
my way through the archive,

00:40:34.940 --> 00:40:36.820
and just reading as much as I can.

00:40:36.820 --> 00:40:39.170
For example, I didn't know when I
started this book that I was going

00:40:39.170 --> 00:40:41.070
to be reading mountains
of Puritan sermons.

00:40:41.070 --> 00:40:44.590
Had I known that, I probably
wouldn't have attempted this book.

00:40:44.590 --> 00:40:46.190
Not really good for the
soul [background laughter].

00:40:46.190 --> 00:40:49.670
And I don't start till I really
-- till the material starts to,

00:40:49.670 --> 00:40:51.730
in some way, marinate or ferment,

00:40:51.730 --> 00:40:55.130
or whatever verb you
want to use, in my mind.

00:40:55.130 --> 00:41:00.000
I knew Anne Foster was going
to be the way into the story,

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:02.720
but you're always surprised
by what you find.

00:41:02.720 --> 00:41:06.470
And the whole idea is, in a funny
way, to have a very open mind

00:41:06.470 --> 00:41:09.290
when you first begin a project.

00:41:09.290 --> 00:41:11.030
Because you don't really
-- if you follow your --

00:41:11.030 --> 00:41:13.160
if you follow a thesis
through the woods,

00:41:13.160 --> 00:41:14.640
you're going to end up
proving your thesis.

00:41:14.640 --> 00:41:18.640
And especially in this case, where
I felt it really incumbent on me

00:41:18.640 --> 00:41:21.500
to leave the answers to the
end of the book so that it read

00:41:21.500 --> 00:41:24.760
as a thriller, with the real
explanations on the end.

00:41:24.760 --> 00:41:29.740
That was important, as was the
idea of conveying what it felt

00:41:29.740 --> 00:41:33.180
like to live and breathe
the New England air in 1692.

00:41:33.180 --> 00:41:34.480
What did these people dream about?

00:41:34.480 --> 00:41:35.780
What did they fear?

00:41:35.780 --> 00:41:37.130
What were their preoccupations?

00:41:37.130 --> 00:41:38.430
What were their obsessions?

00:41:38.430 --> 00:41:39.730
What were they yearning for?

00:41:39.730 --> 00:41:41.740
And that was something I hadn't
found in a previous book.

00:41:41.740 --> 00:41:43.990
And I'm being told we
have one minute left.

00:41:43.990 --> 00:41:45.290
So if you have a quick question --

00:41:45.290 --> 00:41:49.170
&gt;&gt; Question: Yes, so I was
just wondering about the extent

00:41:49.170 --> 00:41:50.470
of the research that you do.

00:41:50.470 --> 00:41:52.950
Like, did you find
yourself in a courtroom?

00:41:52.950 --> 00:41:55.110
Did you find yourself
talking to like,

00:41:55.110 --> 00:41:57.060
a geologist about like
what the rocks looked like?

00:41:57.060 --> 00:41:58.910 position:56%
Or you know, kind of just, what kind

00:41:58.910 --> 00:42:00.310
of wood did they use
to build their cabins.

00:42:00.310 --> 00:42:04.110
Like did you actually sit
in a courtroom and see how

00:42:04.110 --> 00:42:06.400
that would be displayed even
though it was still rough

00:42:06.400 --> 00:42:07.700
like [inaudible] --

00:42:07.700 --> 00:42:10.640
&gt;&gt; Stacy Schiff: I try to get as
close as I can to ground-level.

00:42:10.640 --> 00:42:13.280
This is harder when you're
writing about Cleopatra, you know,

00:42:13.280 --> 00:42:15.830
in a world that -- I mean
Cleopatra's Egypt is gone.

00:42:15.830 --> 00:42:18.380
Only the coast -- not even the
coast is in the right place.

00:42:18.380 --> 00:42:20.590
The moon is in the right
place; that's about it.

00:42:20.590 --> 00:42:24.070
So this was a little bit easier,
but it's very hard to recreate.

00:42:24.070 --> 00:42:25.800
At one point, I said to
an archivist, you know,

00:42:25.800 --> 00:42:27.570
"What did the houses smell like?"

00:42:27.570 --> 00:42:30.150
And he said, you know, "Go
to Plymouth Plantation."

00:42:30.150 --> 00:42:31.450
Brilliant!

00:42:31.450 --> 00:42:32.750
I hadn't thought of it.

00:42:32.750 --> 00:42:34.440
And I went to Plymouth Plantation
and I said to the women --

00:42:34.440 --> 00:42:35.890
"What are the" -- the
women reenactors --

00:42:35.890 --> 00:42:37.700
"What are the worst
months of the year?"

00:42:37.700 --> 00:42:40.810
And every single one of them
said, "January and February".

00:42:40.810 --> 00:42:43.560
Which, of course, is precisely
when the witchcraft broke out.

00:42:43.560 --> 00:42:44.860
Just saying.

00:42:44.860 --> 00:42:47.290
Anyway, thank you very much.

